---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import KpiCard from '../components/KpiCard.astro';
import ChartCard from '../components/ChartCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Green Grid Dashboard">
    <Header />
    
    <Hero />

    <div class="row g-4 mb-5">
        <KpiCard 
            title="Estimated Savings" 
            valueId="kpi-savings" 
            defaultValue="$0.00" 
            subtitle="From solar self-consumption" 
        />
        <KpiCard 
            title="Total Solar Generated" 
            valueId="kpi-solar" 
            defaultValue="0 kWh" 
            subtitle="Clean energy produced" 
        />
        <KpiCard 
            title="Peak Load Hour" 
            valueId="kpi-peak" 
            defaultValue="0:00" 
            subtitle="Highest grid stress" 
        />
    </div>

    <div class="row g-4 justify-content-center">
        <div class="col-12 mt-4 mb-2">
            <div class="px-2">
                <h3 class="h5 text-success fw-bold">One Neighborhood, Different Needs</h3>
                <p class="text-secondary mb-0">Not every home uses energy the same way. While our Studios represent efficient, low-impact living, our Luxury households drive higher demand but also provide a larger surface area for solar collection. By balancing these different profiles, the neighborhood ensures that surplus energy from one can eventually support the stability of the whole.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <ChartCard title="Production vs. Consumption by House Type" chartId="chart1">
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 1:</strong> Compares how much energy each family type needs versus how much they can generate from their specific solar array.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>

        <ChartCard title="Production vs. Consumption by Wealth Level" chartId="chart2">
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 2:</strong> Visualizes the socio-economic impact on energy flow; higher wealth levels often correlate with larger energy footprints and production capacity.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>

        <ChartCard title="Energy Destination & Grid Export" chartId="chart3">
            <Fragment slot="header-text">
                <h6 class="text-success fw-bold mt-3">Where does the sun go?</h6>
                <p class="text-secondary small mb-4">Generation is only half the battle; efficiency is the other. Our system prioritizes "Self-Consumption", using your own solar energy to power your lights and charge your batteries before even thinking about the grid. This maximizes your ROI and keeps the local energy "behind the meter."</p>
            </Fragment>
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 3:</strong> Breakdown of solar utilization. "Self-consumed" energy stays in the neighborhood, while "Exported" energy represents the surplus sold back to the utility grid.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>

        <ChartCard title="The Duck Curve & Grid Stress" chartId="chart4">
            <Fragment slot="header-text">
                <h6 class="text-success fw-bold mt-3">The Challenge: The Afternoon Ramp</h6>
                <p class="text-secondary small mb-4">As the sun sets, solar production drops just as families arrive home and turn on their appliances. This creates the famous "Duck Curve", a massive spike in grid demand. Our smart Energy Management System (EMS) uses battery storage to "flatten" this curve, preventing grid blackouts and reducing high-cost energy imports during peak hours.</p>
            </Fragment>
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 4:</strong> The "Belly" of the duck shows surplus solar at noon. The "Neck" shows the evening peak. Our goal is to keep the blue Net Load line as flat as possible.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>

        <ChartCard title="Battery Storage Utilization" chartId="chart5">
            <Fragment slot="header-text">
                <h6 class="text-success fw-bold mt-3">Storing Sunlight for the Night</h6>
                <p class="text-secondary small mb-4">Our batteries are the heart of the community. They charge silently during the quiet morning hours when the sun is at its peak and discharge strategically when the grid is most expensive. This is the "buffer" that makes energy independence possible.</p>
            </Fragment>
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 5:</strong> Shows the average State of Charge (SoC) across the neighborhood. Notice how the batteries reach 100% capacity just before the sun starts to set.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>

        <ChartCard title="Energy Independence by Wealth Level" chartId="chart7">
            <Fragment slot="header-text">
                <h6 class="text-success fw-bold mt-3">The Path to Independence</h6>
                <p class="text-secondary small mb-4">True success is measured by how little we depend on the traditional utility company. By looking at our energy mix, we can see that a significant portion of our daily life is now powered entirely by the sky, regardless of the wealth level of the household.</p>
            </Fragment>
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 7:</strong> Proportional comparison between solar energy used and the remaining energy we still need to import from the grid.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>

        <ChartCard title="Cost Savings vs. Energy Export per Household" chartId="chart6" columnClass="col-md-6 mx-auto">
            <Fragment slot="header-text">
                <h6 class="text-success fw-bold mt-3 text-start">Every Home is a Winner</h6>
                <p class="text-secondary small mb-4 text-start">Finally, let's analyze the individual performance of our more than 45 households. Each bubble represents a home. The higher the bubble, the more money that family saved. The further to the right, the more they contributed to grid stability by exporting clean energy. This is decentralized energy in action.</p>
            </Fragment>
            <Fragment slot="footer-text">
                <strong>Chart 6:</strong> The "Project Leaf" view: The size of the bubble represents the home's total consumption. This identifies which specific households are achieving the highest financial efficiency.
            </Fragment>
        </ChartCard>
    </div>
</BaseLayout>